<section>
  <h2>Implementation Walkthrough</h2>

  <p>
    The implementation follows a staged approach so each network component can
    be understood, validated, and expanded over time.
  </p>

  <h3>1. Create the VPC</h3>
  <p>
    A dedicated VPC establishes the isolated network boundary for the
    environment and defines the primary CIDR range used by the architecture.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Define Public and Private Subnets</h3>
  <p>
    Subnets divide the VPC address space into separate network tiers. Public
    subnets support resources that require internet-facing connectivity, while
    private subnets support internal workloads.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Attach the Internet Gateway</h3>
  <p>
    The Internet Gateway enables internet connectivity for resources in public
    subnets when paired with the appropriate route table configuration.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Configure Route Tables</h3>
  <p>
  Each subnet is explicitly associated with its intended route table. Both
  route tables retain the VPC local route, while only the public route table
  includes a default route to the Internet Gateway. This creates distinct
  routing behavior without preventing permitted communication inside the VPC.
</p>

  <h3>5. Apply Security Controls</h3>
  <p>
    Security groups provide resource-level traffic control by defining allowed
    inbound and outbound communication patterns.
  </p>

  <h3>6. Validate the Design</h3>
  <p>
    The completed environment can be reviewed through Terraform output, AWS
    console verification, and connectivity testing as additional workloads are
    added.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Validation and Testing</h2>

  <p>
    After deployment, the networking environment was validated to ensure each
    component functioned as designed and provided a solid foundation for future
    workloads.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Verified successful Terraform deployment without errors.</li>
    <li>Confirmed the VPC and subnets were created with the expected CIDR ranges.</li>
    <li>Validated Internet Gateway attachment to the VPC.</li>
    <li>Verified route table associations for public and private subnets.</li>
    <li>Confirmed security groups were applied with the intended traffic rules.</li>
    <li>Reviewed the completed topology within the AWS Management Console.</li>
    <li>Prepared the environment for future deployment of EC2 instances and additional networking services.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section>
  <h2>Lessons Learned</h2>

  <p>
    Building this networking foundation reinforced that successful cloud
    architecture depends as much on thoughtful planning as it does on technical
    implementation. Designing the network before deploying resources resulted
    in a cleaner, more scalable architecture and highlighted the importance of
    making intentional design decisions early in the project lifecycle.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      Careful CIDR planning simplifies future expansion and helps avoid
      unnecessary network redesign.
    </li>

    <li>
      Public and private subnet separation provides a clear security boundary
      and establishes a foundation for layered network security.
    </li>

    <li>
      Infrastructure as Code makes cloud environments repeatable, consistent,
      and significantly easier to maintain than manual deployments.
    </li>

    <li>
      Architecture diagrams and documentation are valuable engineering assets,
      not simply project deliverables. Keeping them synchronized with the
      infrastructure improves maintainability and communication.
    </li>

    <li>
      Small architectural decisions made early in a project can significantly
      influence future scalability, security, and operational simplicity.
    </li>
    <li>
      A subnet becomes public through its route-table association and a default
      route to an Internet Gateway; the subnet name alone does not determine its
      reachability.
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

